The paper presents a data structure for storing compressed sequences and focuses on fundamental building blocks for compressed data structures such as \access, \rank, and \select. This suggests that the paper belongs to the category of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses techniques for compressing the redundancy in highly compressible sequences, which is related to information theory (cs.IT). The use of partitioning the alphabet into characters of similar frequency suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also mentions applications to data compression (cs.DC) and dynamic collections of disjoint sets (cs.SE).
